Sometimes a system can become unresponsive and attempts to shut down properly just don't work.
You've little choice when this happens.
You don't want to be doing this regularly.
As for hardware damage, what I was taught was to avoid rapid off-on and on-off cycles.
Today's power supplies may be better than some of yesterdays but they still like to sequence on and off in a controlled fashion.
If you need to pull the plug to shut down your machine, wait several seconds before applying power again.
This gives circuits time to bleed off stored current before being hit again.
Long ago, I was taught to count to at least 10.
That's not a hard and fast rule, however.
